# Getting Started with IoT and ESP32

The Internet of Things (IoT) is transforming how we interact with the physical world. In this post, I'll walk you through building your first IoT project using an ESP32 microcontroller.

## What You'll Need

- ESP32 Development Board
- DHT11 Temperature & Humidity Sensor
- Breadboard & Jumper Wires
- USB Cable
- Arduino IDE

## Setting Up

First, install the ESP32 board package in Arduino IDE. Go to **File > Preferences** and add the ESP32 board manager URL.

## Reading Sensor Data

```cpp
#include <DHT.h>
#define DHTPIN 4
#define DHTTYPE DHT11
DHT dht(DHTPIN, DHTTYPE);

void setup() {
  Serial.begin(115200);
  dht.begin();
}

void loop() {
  float humidity = dht.readHumidity();
  float temperature = dht.readTemperature();
  Serial.printf("Temp: %.1f°C, Humidity: %.1f%%\n", temperature, humidity);
  delay(2000);
}
```

## Connecting to Firebase

Once you can read sensor data, the next step is sending it to Firebase for real-time visualization. This is exactly what I built for my Smart Sensor Dashboard project!

Stay tuned for Part 2 where we'll set up the Firebase connection and build a real-time web dashboard.
